license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I was inspired by design http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:645203 but inevitable it didn't fit my printer bed and glass size!

I had tried using bulldog clips but these interfered with the auto bed leveling sensor some times.

As you will see from the drawing I measured the distance from the edge of the heated bed to the glass edge when the glass is centered. In my case it was 12mm from the front/back edges and 4mm from the side.

When you load your design in the slicer you will need to flip the design by 180 degrees which will avoid the overhangs.

Making the arms 25mm long provided enough stiffness to keep the glass in position.
I have also made the bracket 1mm higher than the glass, this is to allow for the clips to hold the glass down as the flat edge that holds the glass in place is only 3 mm high.

The design relies upon using the bed leveling screws to hold the clip in place, you may therefore need to replace the original screws with a longer one. You should only need two of these in opposite corners of the bed. If you want or need the other two corners then just use "mirror" in your slicer to produce the mirror copy of the design

I used Autodesk Fusion 360 for the design.

description.text:
These nipple shields are designed to stretch the nipple slightly. The ring itself is 6mm tall and 12mm in diameter. I am including two versions - the smoothed version and the squared version. The smooth version is the one that you want if you're printing as is. I found that modifying something in Sketchup once you've rounded the edges is a PAIN, so I am including the squared version for those who may want to modify it to suit your needs.

There is no hole through the hub because these were designed to have the bar ride on top of the ring. Normally, I would have put an indent in the ring to help center the bar, but the idiot who did my girlfriend's piercings didn't do it straight, so that doesn't work here.

I have not yet been able to talk my girlfriend in to letting me post the photos of these being modeled..... ;)

Tevo Tarantula

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

at least 60% for strength

Notes:

This model is much better suited for SLA printing (or you can get it printed through 3dHubs, Shapeways, etc in SLA) but since no one is offering me a free SLA printer, I have to make do with what I have :)

This does require supports, but I found that the supports would try to fuse to the outer ring, making removal almost impossible. To solve that, I raised the model 3mm off the build plate (making sure that [Automatically Drop to Build Plate] is disabled) and then adding support under that. That makes for a much better support structure that is relatively easy to remove.

If this is printed on a FDM printer, you are going to need to sand the underside of the web really good to get a nice smooth surface. Start with 60 grit sandpaper and work your way up to at least 220 grit. If you have more patience than I do, you can keep going as high as you want. The higher the grit, the smoother your surface will be.

This took me a bit of learning. I use Sketchup for my modeling. Initially, I drew the design as a flat 2D surface and extruded that up. Getting it in to the curved shape took a while. I tried the SketchyFFD and Flowify plugins but neither worked right here. Finally, I found that I could create a semi-circle and use the Sandbox Drape Tool to transfer the 2D pattern onto the surface of the dome. After that, the Joint Push-Pull plugin was used to extrude the curved surfaces upward. Next, I used the RoundCorner plugin to round over the edges. A little cleanup to make the model water tight and voila!

description.text:
I know that this exact design is probably only useful for very few of you, but I still hope other can use it for inspiration. In our house the windows are hinged at the top. It is really nice that we can open the windows and they stay open, without having noises from a window ladge or something.

The only small problem is when you don't want to have the windows wide open, because if they are left just slightly open, they tend to close at the slightest wind.

Therefore I made these airing brackets that will keep the windows 10cm open. The bracket is designed for the specific windows we have (kastrup vinduet, wood-alu); it might fit other windows, but I wouldn't know.

I wanted the bracket to be as strong as possible, so I have not bend the bracket per design. Instead, I printed it lying flat on the printing bed, and then use a hot air gun to heat it and bend it to the desired shape. If you don't have a hot air gun (you should really go get one), I you can also heat the bracket in the oven. This also means that I can use the same bracket in the house, where the windows are 120 cm heigh, and in the workshop, where the windows is only 50 cm heigh.

I designed the bracket with a small tongue that bends downwards to ensure that the window does not hit the end of the bracket.

The design was a bit of a trail and error process. I had to do some adjustments that resulted in a far from professional looking design. However, since it works and fulfill me needs, and since probably not too many of you are going to use this exact thing, I have decided not to spend anymore time on it.

title: Prusa i3 Mk2 x-end stepper motor strain relief

description.text:
This is a quick strain relief part for the x-carriage stepper motor on a Prusa i3 Mk2. Even though the x-carriage doesn't move very much in the z-direction in most prints, I didn't like the fact that there wasn't anything preventing the back-and-forth strain on the wires connecting directly into the x-carriage stepper motor. With two zip ties this can provide much better strain relief, moving the motion of the wires back into the cable wrap, rather than at the wiring harness connection of the motor.

The black zip tie for the cable wrap is one of the extras from the Prusa build, and any small zip tie should work. The zip tie around the motor needs to be longer than the ones provided in the Prusa build packet, so purchase one long enough to go around the stepper motor entirely. The one I used is eight inches, which was almost perfect.

No need for supports. I printed this in PETG in order to have a bit more flex than from PLA, but either should work.

description.text:
I have a Qidi Tech X-One with an Micro Swiss all Metal Hot end and when trying to use SemiFlex the filament kept pushing out the sides. I made the original version and just mirrored it because the Qidi X-One has the trigger on the left side. Either way on the bottom gap where you place a PTFE tube to guide it to the hot end just wouldn't sit where it was supposed to. So I decided to remix this so you no longer need the ptfe tube and the filament should be guided straight into my Micro Swiss All Metal Hot End with out issue. This should work in a stock hot end as well.

As you can see thanks to this extruder mod I was able to get this to Print on the Qidi X-One with no binding, or kinking issues. I find the best way to load the flexible filaments is to give the lever a light press, push the filament in gently until you feel resistance. Let go over the lever and let the machine guide the filament the rest of the way. I find if you press the lever to hard you leave a small gap for the filament to leave the extruder from under the roller and if you keep pushing the filament after the resistance you will see the filament come out the side of the extruder under the roller and not the extruder hole it's supposed to. You need to allow the machine to gently guide the flexible filament out the extruder exit hole and into the hot end. I will look into trying to fix this flaw but this gap is caused by the lever movement and is a necessary gap for the lever to be pushed in the first place.

Use the Left Trigger STL for the Qidi X-One (When pulling this into the slicer it's blown up very large. It should be flat on it's back when imported like the pictures above. From this position if the File imports larger or smaller then it should be the X-Axis Size should be 42.53mm, Y-Axis 32.60mm, Z-Axis 15.01mm. This allows for a very slight shrinkage which Taulman 645 is perfect for.

I left the Right Trigger STL for anyone else who rather use this Extruder Mod over others

Printer:

Qidi X-One

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

30%+

Notes:

I would personally recommend a Taulman Nylon 645 or something similar. The reason being is this is much stronger then ABS, has a Tg of 57C and can with stand over 200C before melting, has some flex but not to much. Very little to no shrinkage so you have less problems with things becoming misaligned because of the shrinkage ABS has. The nylon allows for very little friction (because of it's slick nature) in the down tube that meats the cooling block which is what you want. Also is highly resistant to abrasion. (Tried rubbing it on asphalt with no signs of damage) so this will allow all those abrasive filaments slide right into the extruder while having the strength to withstand the abrasive properties better than our extruder nozzles can. My Qidi can print this with no support but without the support you get globs. Just be aware to use a loose filled support if using nylon or you may not be able to pull the support from the print.

The one thing about using the Nylon where ABS may be the better choice is depending on the ABS your using it may have a much higher Tg. So with this consideration in mind make sure you make the right choice for yourself. If your going to use ABS make sure it's a quality ABS.

After a couple of hundred hours of Running this modification printed in ABS i found no deformations or any other issue with the print.

I am currently using My Taulman Nylon 645 printed version and will update after a couple hundred hours and see how it withstands the heat. So after using this for awhilr there is no defor.ation if the extruder. Also i habe not had any problems what so ever printing any filaments.

description.text:
This kind of structure is NOT my idea. A similar design photo was posted by Jeff Peterson on the FT Facebook page. He has not yet released the files, so I decided to whip up my own. Enjoy!

You'll need 4x of each part. Print the top part upside-down.

Also needed:
8 count of M5x8 and M5 T-nuts
32 count M4x8 and M4 T-nuts

Printer:

Folger Tech 2020 i3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

No

29%

Notes:

I printed out of PLA without supports. These parts have a 60 deg. overhang, so as long as your printer is up to it, and you've got good cooling, you shouldn't need supports. (YMMV)

There doesn't need to be a crazy amount of strength, that comes from the 2020 extrusion, but an infill from 20-40% should be more than acceptable. Anything more is a waste of time and material (in my opinion).

For the FT-5, the base dimensions need to be 500 x 540mm. I designed these so that there is wiggle room in the length needed for the angled 2020.

The sizing of the 2020 is somewhat flexible. You could use smaller lengths in the top box, and make the angled pieces longer, therfore making the entire thing taller. Or youcould to the opposite. For my build, I cut the following lengths:

Top Square:
A: 2 - 200mm
B: 2 - 160mm

Angled Corners:
C: 4 - 190mm

I was able to get this all out of a singe 1.5m stick of 2020.

For the top square to come out to the right size with these lengths, you need to assemble it as shown in the pics, with each piece staggered in the corners (the photo is taken, looking at the bottom of the assembly). Once set, insert the corners (you will need to have at least 2 of the bottom corners not attached to the printer to get this done) and tighten down the screws and t-nuts, making sure everything lines up.

This is a test print I did before working on a different project. There are 6 pieces:
1 top plate
1 base plate
2 pin bases
2 pin caps

The spacing between the cylinders is 0.1 mm, and the spacing between faces is 0.2 mm.

On my print, the pin bases are flush with the bottom of the base plate, and the tops of the pin caps sit about 1 to 2 mm above the top of the upper plate.

It took quite a bit of force to pull the plates apart once it was fully assembled, but, obviously, pulling it apart the first time was the only time it was difficult. After disassembling it and reassembling it for half an hour while watching Futurama, the two faces still hold quite well.

I am posting this because I plan on charging a couple of bucks for the new design I made, and I would like for people to be able to do a test print for free to make sure their printers can handle it. The new design requires 60 pins (120 pieces) to assemble, so I imagine that it would suck to pay for a design and find out that your printer can't do the print.

Tight Tolerances

I highly recommend cleaning up the prints if there is any stringing or artifacting. I had some stringing in my prints, and I had to use my scraper tool to get the parts cleaned up enough to get the pieces to fit.

It took a little bit of force to get everything connected. For some of the pins, I placed the flat part of my scraper tool on the backs of the pin pieces and applied pressure on the printed plates.

Note: The bottom pins should be flush with the bottom face of the base plate. The top pins should stick out about 1-2 mm from the top of the top plate.

title: Side Support for K8400 Print Bed

description.text:
This K8400 upgrade limits bed movement along X-axis. I added two 8mm rods - one on each side of the bed, but single side support may be sufficient as well.

I decided to design these things after seeing the image posted by svdv here https://www.thingiverse.com/make:330539/

Each side requires:

  • one 8mm x 248mm rod
  • one LMU8 (8mm x 15mm x 24mm) linear bearing
  • four M5 x 12mm cup head screws
  • four M5 self-locking nuts
  • four washers for M5 screws
  • one M3 x 25mm screw
  • one M3 self-locking nut
  • two washers for M3 screws
  • two M3 x 20mm cup head screws

If you want to have support from the both sides then double above numbers.

You will also need four M3 x 8mm screws to attach corner pieces to the bed plate.

IMPORTANT: This design requires making four holes for 5mm screws on side panels of the printer and two M3 threaded holes in the aluminium bed as described here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2255250 One more irreversible change - you may need to cut unused, front-facing extensions of the clamps moving along Y-axis rods (parallel to printer sides).

I've done lots of modifications to my K8400, and the following two are affecting this design:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2243656
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2255250
But no worries, for those who did not make above changes, I am publishing the things that should work without them as well. I highlighted the word "should" because I have no way to test how/if they fit.

I'm sharing STL files for one side only. You can mirror them in Repetier Host, or other similar tool.

After assembling and installing all the parts move the bed between top and bottom positions and make sure everything fits. Then mark the spots on the side panels for top and bottom things' mounting screws. The bottom thing should lay on the bottom panel of the printer. Drill the holes, complete assembly and tighten all screws.

literally all i have left right now.

this design is specific to the Monoprice select mini but could
easily be altered to fit any printer if you have the measurements.

--- IMPORTANT ---
when putting the sponge, the slit side should be UP, this will prevent it from ever
coming out, as the filament will not allow it.

Edit:
The purpose of the filter is reduction of hair/dust/particles from getting into and gunking up
the extruder, and it works, the size of the sponge area provided is small. but enough for even 3 days of straight printing in a dusty house (im proof of this).
I couldnt make it larger because then the exit hole on the printed part wouldnt
align with the input to the printer. but if you find away, remix and post here so i can see and

I built the MegaTronXY X! with a 440x440x300 print area, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2326560 but it was to slow, Prints were great but it tock to long to print my Comic-Con items.
Then i built a 220x525 Delta, and that printer printed better then my Factory Purchased Kossel from Ebay. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2358415

405x305, Same height as the 220x525 printer https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2358415

you will also need 24 M3x10 12 M3x16

i ran a time test, i used my Mega Delta any the MegaTronXY X1 and printed identical parts.

and this is what i came up with.

description.text:
Remix of Robin7331's baseplate.
The main modification is this plate is meant to be used with the "Improved Extruder Arm" from vicviper (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1868163) - New See below for my modification of the arm or go to https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2517811.
This required the following modifications:
1) Lowering the height where the elbow of the arm sits.
2) Moved the back wall where the spring sits. The original design had the spring too tight for this arm. New Info: This might create less tension than is needed. Please try my modified arm that allows for adjustable tension (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2517811)

Additional modifications:
1) No need to undo the extruder stepper motor. The hole has been widened so the plate can fit over it.
2) The hole for nut of the pneumatic fiting has been widened since it was a tight fit.
3) The bridge over the gap has been beefed up.
4) The hole for the throat of the tube fitting has been bevelled so it can be tighted and catch the nut easier.

The one issue is that when assembling the plate will want to ride up when the two back screws are tightened. Recommendation is to not tighten all the back screws, and then install the screw for the extruder elbow. Tighten down evenly and maybe hold the front of the plate was doing it so it sits flushed. The slight tilt doesn't effect the alignment in the tube but be careful that the bearing is sitting nicely (aligned) for proper tension on the stepper sprocket.

New:Modified "Improved Extruder Arm" (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2517811) to allow for adjustable tension with a screw. This should increase spring tension.

description.text:
This jig is based off rocklobsters design https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1621437 with a few modifications.

I designed it from scratch in Fusion 360 with a few tweaks to rocklobsters design to get the vice working without the arm falling out when winding it back and to also support the Kreg R3.
I also added in metric and imperial measurements as a guide for your R3 that match up with the ones that mount on the side of the device.

Parts list:
3x M10 nuts
1x 120mm M10 threaded rod
2x Washers
1x M3x25 or 30 mm screw
1x M3 Washer
1x M3 Wingnut
or if you use the locknut method
1x M4x25 or 30 mm screw
1x M4 Washer
1x M4 Wingnut
1x M4 Nylock
Aluminium for the vice face and to mount the jig too ( not shown in my pictures as i'm waiting on it to arrive )

To get the vice to work you will need to create a notch at one end of the rod as shown in the attached pictures - i used a lathe at work to do this but this can be done at home with a drill and a file - refer to http://www.hhhh.org/joeboy/resources/hotwire_foam_cutter/hotwire_foam_cutter.html under BASE heading for an example.
Once notched - cut your washer or obtain a circlip and clip this onto the notch - this will stop the rod from falling out and moving forward when adjusting the vice.

For the turning knob i welded the nut to the other end of the rod and then pushed on printed knob ( tight fitting so force will be needed ) this wont come loose as it's a very tight fit - but you could also add some glue in if you like.
If you dont have a welder - then threadlock and or a nylock will work.

The Kreg M3 hole stl is so you can use the bottom oval hole of the R3 so you can slide the jig up and down and lock it off into position - i created this because the tiny mount inside the R3 will most probably break over time as there isn't much meat there - so i printed this part a tad oversize so some filling will be needed ( depending on your printer ) and then you push it in to the hole i left it fairly tight and used a hammer and screw to push the part into the R3 so it's a nice solid fit and wont dislodge.

description.text:
This hummingbird feeder moat comes in 3 printed parts. The moat bowl, a spacer, and the umbrella on top. Generally moats are a good idea for the hummingbird feeders, but you can either fill them with water daily due to evaporation, or use oil in them. Mineral oil works GREAT, but if you leave it uncovered a good rain will make a mess of your feeders and/or the area where you put your feeders.

My solution was to fabricate a thick walled moat with a beefy center stem in order to accommodate a length of 8 gauge copper wire for a hook (pick up at Home Depot or Lowes). Bend a U in one end of the wire and feed it through the base of the moat. Bend a small dogleg in the wire to keep the moat higher on the wire than the bottom if desired. Once seated, place the 5mm spacer on top of the moat and then the umbrella on top of the spacer. Bend a U in the other end of the copper wire, at least 3 inches above the umbrella to allow for filling and emptying of the moat.

Ants can't get in, and rain can't enter the moat to ruin your oil bath. You can use them for individual feeders or use them to suspend a plant rod and hang your feeders from the rod. My ants congregated on top of the umbrellas for a couple of hours and then gave up. No more ants here. :)

title: e3d v6 adapter for Monoprice Select Mini V1

description.text:
Nearly zero-offset adapter to use e3d v6 hotend with Version 1 of the popular Monoprice Select Mini. Allows use of third-party e3d v6 hotend and nozzles to allow printing with larger variety of filaments. Since I used this with the e3d v6 hotend, no more jagged edges or jams, and it's now a snap to change nozzles.

Note: since there are different nozzle heights, you may have to modify these adapters to avoid dragging along the bed when using shorter nozzles that don't stick out as far from the heater block.

Updated 7/2/2017 - includes an additional backplate that is 4 mm taller to accommodate printing on 3-4 mm borosilicate glass. This new backplate lifts the e3d v6 assembly up by 4 mm, allowing you to use a glass plate without needing to use z-axis limit switch adapter. Note that this adapter may require that you modify how far your nozzle sticks out, as nozzles that are very close to the heater block may be too high, and the x-carriage can hit the bed instead!

Updated 7/8/2017 - includes new front clamp that incorporates fan for heat sink as well as fan with hidden shroud to direct air to help cool extruded filament. Due to the extra depth, the front mount is counter sunk to allow the use of shorter screws. 25-30 mm m3 screws to hold it in place.

Updated 7/18/17 - Includes new front clamp to allow installation of 40 mm fan along with the default fan, and improved an shroud and air director

Updated 7/19/17 - enlarged mounting holes for sinking screw heads, improved alignment, and modified air holes to improve airflow.

Updated 7/25/17 - further refinement in fan shroud to optimize air flow for cooling extruded filament.

Updated 9/13/17 - created a spacer for 40mm fan to allow more air for the e3dv6 adapter 30mm fan. Also printed a small spacer to hold nuts in place while attaching backplate.

Updated 9/16/2017 - smoothed mounting surfaces

Updated 11/5/2017 - created smaller shroud and adapter for 40mm fan, since previous design could drag on the bed/prints if the nozzle wasn't low enough.

Updated 12/2/2017 - 40mm adapter and shroud reworked to redirect air toward plate and away from hotend.

Updated 1/21/2018 - 30mm adapter and shroud reworked to redirect air toward plate and away from hotend, and tweaked to eliminate air leak from secondary fan in early version. Also backplates now reworked to allow nuts to be "press fit", eliminating the need for the previous spacer (see 9/13/17 note above).

Securing top of backplate to x-axis mount

This is an optional step, but I think it adds a lot of stability, especially if using the front mount for double fans.. With the backplate in place, drill a small hole through the top of the x-axis mount and insert a 10-15 mm m3 screw. Since there's no easy way to add a nut, the best thing to do is drill using a bit slightly thinner than the screw (3/32 inch it works well). Since you're screwing directly into the back of the backplate , this is why I suggest using 100% infill. This backplate will last a long time, and you don't want it to fail. I printed out copies to have on hand just in case, but haven't had to use them yet!

Smoothing front of backplate

The backplate has a small channel to help hold the e3d v6 heat sink fins, and a transverse channel to aid in air flow. Because these are printed on the bottom of the backplate, they may require a small amount of filing with Dremel tool or other round file to get them smooth.

Used Tinkercad

Took a lot of trial and error. At first was going to make this longer and wider than the original aluminum block to sit in front of the x-axis mount, but this pushed the e3d v6 hot end too far out, and didn't want to lose build space.

This Dice container can be used to hold/keep dice in, also can be used as a dice cup. Not only for dice obviously, but that was it's original design was aiming for.

V2 has a smaller threading, but the tower cap is scaled 1:1.

This design was inspired by Adafruit's Tower storage and was designed from scratch in 123D Design.

Adafruit Tower Storage : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1924100

Very simple really. Place a cylinder for the base and then transform the top to a taper, then place a much taller cylinder on top dead center to make the tower. Sketch or place a cylinder to remove the inside of the tower(to hollow it out). Use toroids(torus) tool to make thin rings with same mid diameter as the cylinder and space them evenly up the tower and then remove overlapping to get your brick lines. As for the threading, use Torus tool, cut it in half, and tilt at 6 degrees then snap and join.

description.text:
This kit will add rigidity to your Wanhao i3 Plus, Monoprice Select Plus, and other Wanhao Rebranded Clones of this style.

This Mod was created after receiving my Wanhao I3 Plus. Having designed two other braces for the Duplicator I3 V series this was a new undertaking. This mod came as a follow on from my original two designs.

My Goal was to create a Z-Brace Mod that was easy for the beginner to install and not have to drill or change any features about the printer itself.

Do you need a rear mount z-brace?
Maybe not but as I said in my SWD2 version its cool.
Do you need a z-brace in General a resounding "YES" is still the answer.

This rear mount functions exactly like my previous creations.
It stabilizes your z axis so that it is square and does not vibrate creating any ringing in prints or warping of the frame.

Do you need to struggle and try to print this yourself?
No, as I have partnered with Ultimate3dPrintingStore to offer both the Hardware and Printed parts for this for those that are new and struggling to get started.
https://ultimate3dprintingstore.com/collections/brace-kits
(please note the SWD3 kit is not in the U3D store yet, but, is coming soon as logistics for the components is running a little behind schedule.)

Finally this is a rock solid design that incorporates the use of rods to stabilize the printer and for those that have uneven surfaces you are setting your printer on there is levelers.
Please Note: the Levelers are an optional Install but does come with the kit offered by U3DS.

Please visit my friends at the Duplicator i3 (Di3) 3D Printer Group (Wanhao, Monoprice, Cocoon Create...on Facebook as its a great group of people with a enormous amount of knowledge on these printers.

Also visit The 3d Printer Wiki the guys there have a lot of tips tricks and knowledge for those new into 3d printing. Lot of resources for this style of Printer.
http://3dprinterwiki.info/

For Parts/Printers and just about anything you can imagine Wanhao visit my friends at:
https://ultimate3dprintingstore.com

Last but not least if you just want to show me some appreciation for making your printer a rock solid printing monster drop me a dime or two here..
https://www.paypal.me/Shadowweavr2067

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2 layer height

Infill:

15-40% its optional

Notes:

Notably I have stated the print infill percentage can be between 10-40%
With the lower percentage please use more outter shells as two shells is not enough I printed all mine at 4 shells and 12% and they are rock solid and function as needed. .

When using supports use normal supports not just from the bed as you will need them depending on how you place the top z-brackets. If you turn them vertically to reduce supports there will be a slight difference from the upper caps to the upper supports as they were designed laying down.

After Printing you will need to clean up your prints and remove supports.

As a general rule you will need some needle nose plyers or small cutters to access some of the support material.

As a precaution to make the rod installation easier use a 5/16 / 8mm drill bit to clean out the rod paths in the upper and lower braces. Rods can be installed without this but the bit allows for any deburing in the tube.

Installation process.

  1. Ensure Threaded rods are Cut to 410mm in length.

  2. Remove 1) M5x5 screw on front of y axis and 1) M3x5 on the same side on the cover
    plate that its mounted on the bottom.
    Mount New Bracket and replace with 1) M5 x10mm screw
    And 1) M3 x 10mm screw.
    Repeat for opposite side. Be sure to use the blocks for the front of the
    printer please refer to Primary Image.
    Then repeat for rear blocks usng the winged parts for the rods.

  3. Install 4) 1/4-20 nuts in the blocks for the Leveler Feet, When you look at the bottom of
    the blocks you will see the recess for the nuts.
    Then install 4) 1/4-20-3/4 bolts into the printed leveler feet.( see Attached
    Image)

  4. Prep the Threaded Rods for Install. Attach 1) 5/16 nylock nut to one end of the rod,
    thread it on the rod until 1/4 inch of rod is exposed past the nut. Do this to
    both Rods.(See attached pic)

  5. Position the printer so that one side allows the blocks with wings to hang over the edge
    of the table so that you may slide the rods in from the bottom of the block.

  6. Slide the threaded rods up through the block from the bottom approximately half way
    between the z-tower and the wing block. Install in this sequence 1 5/16 nut, 1
    nut cap, (to cover the lower 5/16 nut, Invert the next nut cap, 1) 5/16 nut above
    the two nut caps.

  7. Remove the two M3 bolts on the Side at the top of the Z-axis tower, Slide z-axis mount
    until it lines up with the two side holes and replace with M3 x 10 screws.
    Repeat for opposite side.

9 Slide Rod up and through the Z-axis mount until the Nylock 5/16 Nut seats in the lower
block. Tighten the lower 5/16 nut down to secure the bottom section. Use the
Nylock Nut Cap to tighten the nut.

  1. To Finalize the install add a final 5/16 nut on the top end of the brace mount on the z-
    axis ( adjust and square printer and tighten down the last two nuts at the top of
    the z-axis ) attach top cap with 2) M3 x 10mm screws on each side to complete
    the install

  2. Adjust and level Machine accordingly.

Please Note: There will be a follow on Installation .pdf and video for this kit.
Feel free to contact me for any errors or issues you may have with these instructions and I will correct or change as needed.

title: 1 gallon paint can metal melting furnace interior mold

description.text: A mold for the internal chamber of a paint can furnace using furnace cement. The nozzle of a bernzomatic ts8000 map/propane gas torch goes in through the side with a 10 degree slant towards the top to help disperse the heat from the bottom to the top of the furnace in a vortex. Place part 1 in the bottom center of the can and hot glue it in. Then fill the bottom of the can evenly with 1 1/2 inch or 38mm and let it set. Then put the mold inside of the can centered with the stem against the inside wall of the can where the entrance hole for the torch will be. Fill the rest of the void between the mold and the can with furnace cement and let it cure. I used sand in the center of the cavity of the mold to hold it in place. Cut the entrance hole for the torch in the side of the can and use the torch to burn out the mold. Part 1 is a drain hole in case of crucible failure.

Notes:

Two parts. The top piece is just a decorative piece that hides the M6 bolt to the compression plug or star nut in the steerer. The decorative top has a 22 mm x 3 mm recess in the bottom and friction fits on the base. If you want to actually use the printed top cap base piece to set the preload on the headset you should print it strong. I printed it solid.

Snap out the supports, install the base with bolt from stock top cap (usually M6 x something), snap on the decorative cover. If you insist on printing it thin and light, you could use a normal metal top cap to set the preload, tighten up the stem pinch bolts, then remove the metal top cap and install the printed base as a decorative piece, but I wouldn't want to do that in case you ever need to adjust your stem on the road.

Converted logo from buddies shop to svg and imported as sketch in Fusion 360. Had to recreate most of the circles and some of the curves to close microscopic gaps in the geometry, Then I just created a rough copy of one of my metal top caps and played with the geometry. Iterated until I was happy.

This is a replacement part for the Cuisinart DFP-14 series of food processors. Specifically, the plastic latch that is used as part of the safety mechanism on the bowl cover. It is a nearly-perfect copy of the original part (there is a non-functional difference in one of the edges of the top part) and is a drop-in replacement. I assume that you are re-using the OEM pin that holds it in place -- it works perfectly with this design.

The current version of this part is now printable without supports.

For years I have wondered if I was sharpening knives at the proper angle for their use. I came across something like this on amazon a while back but couldn't justify buying them when I could just make my own. This is just my first draft of these. If you have any suggestion on what I can add let me know. I believe you are supposed to put this block at the end of your stone to get the knife angle then slide your knife along the stone keeping that angle but not dragging the block along. I printed these at a fast speed so they didn't turn out super well in the photos but they still work.

The most popular knife sharpening angles are 17-20 degree's per side. I included the 10, 12, and 15 for things such as xacto blades or razor blades. The 25 and 30 I am not sure what they could be used for. Maybe sharpening an axe or machete? Let me know if you want a specific angle and I will try and design one for you.
